                <!-- First Blog Post -->
                <h2>
                    Getting Started with AngularJS
                </h2>
                <p class="lead">
                    by Megan Balcom
                </p>
               
               <hr>
                <img id="blogImage"class="img-responsive" src="images/angularjs.jpg" alt="AngularJS banner">
                <hr>
                <p>How to build the initial page for this website:</p>
                <h3>1) Initialization (ng-app) </h3>
                <p>The ng-app command is used as an attribute on an element to relay to the angular.js file which part of the webpage to interact with.</p>
                <h3>2) Data </h3>
                <p>An array of objects is stored in the tutorials.json file to be accessed by angular.</p>
                <h3>3) Access (get)</h3>
                <p>The get command allows angular to connect with the .json file in order to access the stored object array.</p>
                <h3>4) Step through objects (ng-repeat)</h3>
                <p>The ng-repeat class allows angular to step through an array of objects printing them to the page.</p>
                <h3>5) Sort (ng-route) </h3>
                <p>The ng-route command enables the page to use filters, in this case, search the stored array of objects by author, title, or url.</p>

            </div>
